Ah, New Brunswick. A city that seems to wear its history like a slightly ill-fitting coat, yet still manages to project an air of persistent relevance. They call it the "Hub City," a moniker that suggests centrality, a nexus of activity. And then there's "Healthcare City," which, frankly, is a bit too on the nose, isn't it? As if to say, "Look at us, we're important because sick people come here." It’s a label that, while factual, lacks a certain… flair.

Let's dive into the dense, often contradictory tapestry that is New Brunswick, New Jersey.

## New Brunswick, New Jersey: The Hub and the Hospital

New Brunswick, a city nestled within [Middlesex County](/Middlesex_County,_New_Jersey), holds the distinction of being the county seat. It’s a place that straddles the line between a vibrant [college town](/College_town), primarily due to the sprawling presence of [Rutgers University](/Rutgers_University), and a commuter's haven, with many of its residents making the daily trek to the behemoth that is [New York City](/New_York_City) within the greater [New York metropolitan area](/New_York_metropolitan_area). Its strategic location on the [Northeast Corridor rail line](/Northeast_Corridor) places it a mere 27 miles (43 km) southwest of the Big Apple, a geographical advantage that shapes its very identity. Situated on the southern banks of the [Raritan River](/Raritan_River), it’s a significant player in the Raritan Valley Region.

As of the [2020 United States census](/2020_United_States_census), New Brunswick housed 55,266 souls. This represented a marginal increase of 85 people, or 0.2%, from the 2010 census figure of 55,181. The preceding decade, from 2000 to 2010, had seen a more substantial uptick of 6,608 residents, a 13.6% jump. The [U.S. Census Bureau's](/United_States_Census_Bureau) most recent estimates, from 2023, place the population at 55,846. This makes it the 719th most populous municipality in the nation, and within New Jersey, it ranks 37th out of 565 municipalities and second within Middlesex County.

The city’s abundant medical facilities, including [Robert Wood Johnson University Hospital](/Robert_Wood_Johnson_University_Hospital), its associated [medical school](/Robert_Wood_Johnson_Medical_School), and [Saint Peter's University Hospital](/Saint_Peter%27s_University_Hospital), have cemented its reputation as both the "Hub City" and "Healthcare City." It's also a major corporate hub for global pharmaceutical giants like [Johnson & Johnson](/Johnson_%26_Johnson) and [Bristol Myers Squibb](/Bristol_Myers_Squibb). Over time, New Brunswick has cultivated a reputation as a center for scientific advancement, artistic expression, and cultural activities. The downtown area is notably undergoing a transformation, with new [high-rise towers](/Tower_block) beginning to punctuate its [skyline](/Skyline).

New Brunswick is also recognized for its considerable [ethnic diversity](/Ethnic_diversity). At one point, a quarter of New Jersey's Hungarian population called this city home, and by the 1930s, one in every three residents was Hungarian. This community remains a strong presence, with its 3,200 residents constituting 8% of the city's population in 1992. More recently, significant [Asian](/Asian_American) and [Hispanic](/Hispanic) communities have flourished, particularly around French Street, near the aforementioned Robert Wood Johnson University Hospital.

### History

#### Etymology

The land that now constitutes New Brunswick was originally inhabited by the [Lenape](/Lenape) [Native Americans](/Native_Americans_of_the_United_States). Their Minisink Trail, a vital artery, intersected the [Raritan River](/Raritan_River) and followed a path that would later be adopted by colonial roads. The first European settlement at this location dates back to 1681. Initially known as Prigmore's Swamp (1681–1697), it later became known as Inian's Ferry (1691–1714). In 1714, the settlement was christened New Brunswick, a tribute to the city of [Braunschweig](/Braunschweig) (or Brunswick in [Low German](/Low_German)) in the German state of [Lower Saxony](/Lower_Saxony). Braunschweig itself was a formidable city within the [Hanseatic League](/Hanseatic_League) and served as an administrative center for the Duchy of Hanover. Coincidentally, shortly after New Brunswick’s initial settlement, George, Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg and Elector of Hanover, ascended to the British throne as [King George I of Great Britain](/George_I_of_Great_Britain). An alternative, and perhaps more widely accepted, etymology suggests the city is named in honor of King [George II of Great Britain](/George_II_of_Great_Britain), who also held the title [Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg](/Duchy_of_Brunswick-L%C3%BCneburg).

#### Colonial and Early American Periods

Positioned strategically between [New York City](/New_York_City) and [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia,_Pennsylvania) along the King's Highway, and situated on the banks of the [Raritan River](/Raritan_River), New Brunswick quickly established itself as a crucial nexus for colonial travelers and merchants. The town was officially incorporated in 1736, and subsequently chartered as a city in 1784. Its administrative structure was further refined in 1798 when it was incorporated into a town under the [Township Act of 1798](/Township_Act_of_1798). During the [Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War), the city fell under British occupation during the winter of 1776–1777.

The [Declaration of Independence](/United_States_Declaration_of_Independence) received one of its earliest public readings in New Brunswick on July 9, 1776, just days after its official promulgation by the [Continental Congress](/Continental_Congress). This significant historical moment is now commemorated by a bronze statue in Monument Square, a tribute dedicated on July 9, 2017, located in front of The Heldrich Hotel.

The Trustees of Queen's College, established in 1766 (and known today as [Rutgers University](/Rutgers_University)), made the pivotal decision in 1771 to locate the nascent institution in New Brunswick, choosing it over [Hackensack](/Hackensack,_New_Jersey) in [Bergen County, New Jersey](/Bergen_County,_New_Jersey). Classes commenced in 1771 with a single instructor and one sophomore, [Matthew Leydt](/Matthew_Leydt), alongside several freshmen, convening at a tavern known as the 'Sign of the Red Lion' at the corner of Albany and Neilson Streets (now the site of the [Johnson & Johnson](/Johnson_%26_Johnson) corporate headquarters). Leydt would go on to become the university's first graduate in 1774, being the sole member of that graduating class. The 'Sign of the Red Lion' was acquired by Queen's College in 1771 and later sold to the estate of [Jacob Rutsen Hardenbergh](/Jacob_Rutsen_Hardenbergh) in 1791. Throughout the American Revolution, classes were held in various taverns and boarding houses, as well as in a building on George Street known as College Hall, until the completion of [Old Queens](/Old_Queens) in 1811. Old Queens remains the oldest building on the Rutgers campus. The Queen's College Grammar School, which evolved into [Rutgers Preparatory School](/Rutgers_Preparatory_School), was also established in 1766 and shared facilities with the college until 1830, when it relocated to a building across College Avenue from Old Queens, now known as [Alexander Johnston Hall](/Alexander_Johnston_Hall). Following Rutgers University's designation as the state university of New Jersey in 1945, the Trustees divested Rutgers Preparatory School, which subsequently relocated in 1957 to an estate in [Franklin Township](/Franklin_Township,_Somerset_County,_New_Jersey), [Somerset County](/Somerset_County,_New_Jersey), purchased from [Colgate-Palmolive](/Colgate-Palmolive).

The [New Brunswick Theological Seminary](/New_Brunswick_Theological_Seminary), founded in 1784 in [New York](/New_York_(state)), relocated to New Brunswick in 1810, sharing its facilities with the then-struggling Queen's College. (Queen's College experienced a closure from 1810 to 1825 due to financial difficulties, reopening in 1825 as Rutgers College.) The Seminary, citing overcrowding and disagreements over Rutgers College's secular mission, eventually moved to a 7-acre (2.8 ha) tract of land about half a mile to the west, a site it continues to occupy today, now situated in the midst of Rutgers University's [College Avenue Campus](/College_Avenue_Campus).

New Brunswick was formally established by [royal charter](/Royal_charter) on December 30, 1730, encompassing parts of [Middlesex](/Middlesex_County,_New_Jersey) and [Somerset](/Somerset_County,_New_Jersey) counties. It was re-established by royal charter with the same boundaries on February 12, 1763, at which point it was divided into north and south wards. The city's current boundaries were solidified by an act of the [New Jersey Legislature](/New_Jersey_Legislature) on September 1, 1784, when it was officially incorporated as a city.

