#### African-American Community

##### Slavery in New Brunswick

The presence of an African-American community in New Brunswick traces its origins back to the 18th century, a period when racial slavery was an ingrained part of life in the city and its surrounding environs. Slaveholders in New Brunswick routinely engaged in the buying and selling of African American individuals, including children, women, and men, particularly in the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries. During this era, the Market-House, situated at the intersection of Hiram and Queen Streets (now Neilson Street), adjacent to the Raritan Wharf, served as the epicenter of the city's commercial activity. This locale was not only a hub for residents to trade their goods but also a regular venue for slave auctions and sales.

By the close of the eighteenth century, New Brunswick had emerged as a significant center for newspaper production and distribution. The Fredonian, a widely circulated newspaper, was located just a block away from the aforementioned Market-House, contributing to the facilitation of commercial transactions. Prominently featured within the pages of these local newspapers were advertisements from private owners seeking to sell their slaves. This practice underscores a preference among New Brunswick residents for private, individual slave sales over larger group transactions. The majority of these individual advertisements were for female slaves, with the average age at the time of sale being approximately 20 years old – an age considered prime for childbearing. Slave owners profited immensely from these women, as they represented the potential to generate future generations of enslaved laborers. Furthermore, in the urban setting of New Brunswick, the demand for domestic labor was high, and female workers were particularly sought after for household tasks such as cooking and cleaning.

The [New Jersey Legislature](/New_Jersey_Legislature) enacted "An Act for the Gradual Abolition of Slavery" in 1804. This legislation stipulated that children born to enslaved women after July 4, 1804, would be bound to service for their master for a term of 21 years if female, or 25 years if male, after which they would gain their freedom. However, individuals who were already enslaved prior to July 4, 1804, remained slaves for life, with no provision for their emancipation under this law. Consequently, New Brunswick continued to be home to enslaved African Americans, alongside a burgeoning community of free Black individuals. The [1810 United States census](/1810_United_States_census) recorded 53 free Black individuals and 164 slaves within New Brunswick.

##### African American Spaces and Institutions in the Early 19th Century

By the 1810s, a segment of the free African-American population resided in an area known as Halfpenny Town, situated along the [Raritan River](/Raritan_River) on the eastern side of the city, near Queen (now Neilson) Street. Halfpenny Town was characterized by a mixed population of free Black individuals and poorer white residents who did not own slaves. This area served as a social gathering place for free Black people, offering a degree of respite from pervasive white scrutiny and allowing for self-directed socialization. Nevertheless, it was not entirely free from white observation and continued to bear the negative influences of the slavery era. In the early decades of the nineteenth century, white residents and African Americans, both free and enslaved, frequently shared communal spaces, particularly places of worship. The First Presbyterian Church, Christ Church, and the First Reformed Church were popular among both racial groups, and New Brunswick was notable for its scarcity of spaces designated exclusively for African American congregation. In most instances, Black congregants within these churches remained under the watchful eyes of white members. This situation persisted until the establishment of the African Association of New Brunswick in 1817.

Both free and enslaved African Americans actively participated in the founding of the African Association of New Brunswick, which commenced its meetings in 1817. The Association convened monthly, primarily in the homes of free Black individuals, though occasional meetings were held at the First Presbyterian Church. Initially conceived to provide financial support for the African School of New Brunswick, the African Association evolved into a crucial space for Black individuals to congregate, share ideas, and discuss topics ranging from religion to abolition and colonization. Enslaved individuals were required to obtain a pass from their owners to attend these meetings. The African Association collaborated closely with white residents and generally received favor from them, as they believed it would foster greater racial harmony and peace within New Brunswick.

The African Association of New Brunswick established the African School in 1822. The school’s initial location was in the home of Caesar Rappleyea in 1823. The school was situated at the upper end of Church Street in downtown New Brunswick, approximately two blocks from the jail where escaped slaves were held. Both free and enslaved Black individuals were permitted to be members of the School. Reverend Huntington, the pastor of the [First Presbyterian Church](/First_Presbyterian_Church_(New_Brunswick,_New_Jersey)), and several other prominent white individuals served as trustees of the African Association of New Brunswick. These trustees offered their support to the Association, which provided a sense of security for slave owners who permitted their slaves to attend via a permission slip system. The prevailing sentiment among these white supporters was that Black individuals were not yet suited for American citizenship and residence, and some trustees were affiliated with the [American Colonization Society](/American_Colonization_Society), an organization that advocated for the repatriation of free African Americans to Africa. While the white trustees attended only some of the Association's meetings, the organization represented an unprecedented space for both enslaved and free Black individuals to gather with minimal white oversight.

The African Association appears to have disbanded sometime after 1824. By 1827, free and enslaved Black individuals in the city, including Joseph and Jane Hoagland, united to establish the Mount Zion [African Methodist Episcopal Church](/African_Methodist_Episcopal_Church) and acquired a plot of land on Division Street for the construction of a church building. This marked the establishment of the first African American church in Middlesex County. The church initially had around 30 members and continues to operate today at 39 Hildebrand Way. The street itself is named in honor of the late Rev. Henry Alphonso Hildebrand, who served as pastor of Mount Zion AME for an impressive 37 years, the longest tenure of any pastor at the church.

Census records from April 1828 indicate that New Brunswick had a population of 4,435 white residents and 374 free African Americans. The enslaved population at that time consisted of 57 individuals bound for life and 127 eligible for emancipation at ages 21 or 25, as per the 1804 Act for the Gradual Abolition of Slavery. In 1828, free and enslaved African Americans constituted 11% of New Brunswick's population, a notably high proportion for New Jersey. For context, the [1830 United States census](/1830_United_States_census) reported that African Americans made up approximately 6.4% of New Jersey's total population.

##### Jail and Curfew in the 19th Century

In 1824, the New Brunswick Common Council instituted a curfew specifically for free Black individuals, prohibiting them from being out after 10 p.m. on Saturdays. The Council also formed a committee of white residents tasked with apprehending and detaining any free African Americans deemed "out of place" by white authorities.

New Brunswick gained notoriety as a haven for slave hunters, who actively enforced the [Fugitive Slave Act of 1850](/Fugitive_Slave_Act_of_1850). Its strategic location on the Raritan River also made it a crucial hub for New Jersey's [Underground Railroad](/Underground_Railroad). For runaway slaves seeking passage to New York and Canada, New Brunswick presented a favorable route. However, escapees attempting to travel to or from New Brunswick faced a high probability of capture and subsequent detainment in the city's jail, then located on Prince Street, now known as Bayard Street.

#### Hungarian Community

The Committee of Hungarian Churches and Organizations of New Brunswick commemorating the anniversary of the [Hungarian Revolution of 1956](/1956_Hungarian_Revolution)

New Brunswick has been lauded as the nation's "most Hungarian city." Hungarian immigrants began arriving as early as 1888, and by 1915, they constituted nearly 20% of the city's population. The primary draw for Hungarians was employment opportunities at the Johnson & Johnson factories situated within the city. The Hungarian community primarily settled in what is now the [Fifth Ward](/Fifth_Ward,_New_Brunswick), and numerous businesses emerged to cater to the specific needs of this immigrant population, which were not adequately met by mainstream establishments. The immigrant population continued to grow until the cessation of the large-scale immigration wave in the early 20th century.

During the [Cold War](/Cold_War), the community experienced a resurgence due to the decision to process tens of thousands of refugees fleeing the failed [1956 Hungarian Revolution](/1956_Hungarian_Revolution) at [Camp Kilmer](/Camp_Kilmer), located in nearby [Edison](/Edison,_New_Jersey). Despite the Hungarian population having been largely assimilated by newer immigrant groups, an annual [Hungarian Festival](/Hungarian_Festival) continues to be held on Somerset Street on the first Saturday of June each year; the 44th iteration took place in 2019. Many Hungarian institutions, established by the community, remain active and vibrant in the neighborhood. These include: Magyar Reformed Church, Ascension Lutheran Church, St. Ladislaus Roman Catholic Church, St. Joseph Byzantine Catholic Church, Hungarian American Athletic Club, Aprokfalva Montessori Preschool, Széchenyi Hungarian Community School & Kindergarten, Teleki Pál Scout Home, Hungarian American Foundation, Vers Hangja, Hungarian Poetry Group, Bolyai Lecture Series on Arts and Sciences, Hungarian Alumni Association, Hungarian Radio Program, Hungarian Civic Association, Committee of Hungarian Churches and Organizations of New Brunswick, and the Csűrdöngölő Folk Dance Ensemble.

Several landmarks within the city serve as testaments to its rich Hungarian heritage. Streets and parks bear the names of [Lajos Kossuth](/Lajos_Kossuth), a key leader of the [Hungarian Revolution of 1848](/Hungarian_Revolution_of_1848). The intersection of Somerset Street and Plum Street has been designated Mindszenty Square, where the first statue of Cardinal [József Mindszenty](/J%C3%B3zsef_Mindszenty) was erected. Nearby, a stone memorial honors the victims of the 1956 Hungarian Revolution.

#### Latino Community

According to the 2010 Census, approximately 50% of New Brunswick's population identified as Hispanic, placing it 14th among New Jersey municipalities for this demographic. Since the 1960s, a significant influx of new residents has arrived from Latin America, with many citizens migrating from Puerto Rico in the 1970s. The 1980s saw substantial immigration from the Dominican Republic, followed by later waves from Guatemala, Honduras, Ecuador, and Mexico.

#### Demolition, Revitalization, and Redevelopment

The [Gateway Project](/The_Gateway_(New_Brunswick,_New_Jersey)) under construction, a symbol of the city's ongoing development.
College Avenue, showcasing a striking [juxtaposition](/Juxtaposition) of historical and contemporary architecture.

New Brunswick is recognized as one of nine cities in New Jersey designated as eligible for Urban Transit Hub Tax Credits by the state's [Economic Development Authority](/New_Jersey_Economic_Development_Authority). This program offers tax credits to developers who invest a minimum of $50 million within a half-mile radius of a train station.

New Brunswick exemplifies various approaches to [urban renewal](/Urban_renewal) in the United States. During the 1960s and 1970s, the downtown area experienced significant [urban decay](/Urban_decay), a trend often associated with "[white flight](/White_flight)," as middle-class residents relocated to the surrounding suburbs. In response, starting in 1975, [Rutgers University](/Rutgers_University%E2%80%93New_Brunswick), [Johnson & Johnson](/Johnson_%26_Johnson), and the city government formed a collaborative entity, the New Brunswick Development Company (DevCo), with the explicit aim of revitalizing the city center and redeveloping neighborhoods deemed blighted or unsafe through demolition and new construction. In 1978, Johnson & Johnson announced its commitment to remaining in New Brunswick and investing $50 million to construct a new global headquarters. This ambitious project necessitated the demolition of numerous older buildings and historic streets in the area bounded by Albany Street, Amtrak's Northeast Corridor, Route 18, and George Street. The Hiram Market area, a historic district that had become a predominantly Puerto Rican and Dominican-American neighborhood by the 1970s, was razed to make way for a [Hyatt](/Hyatt) hotel and conference center, along with upscale housing. Johnson & Johnson provided financial guarantees for the Hyatt Hotels investment, demonstrating their confidence in the revitalized area.

Devco, the local hospitals, and the city government have faced criticism from [historic preservationists](/Historic_preservation), those opposing [gentrification](/Gentrification), and individuals concerned about alleged abuses of [eminent domain](/Eminent_domain) and excessive tax abatements for developers.

New Brunswick is home to the primary campus of [Rutgers University](/Rutgers_University%E2%80%93New_Brunswick) and the world headquarters of [Johnson & Johnson](/Johnson_%26_Johnson), which established its new [headquarters](/Headquarters) in the city in 1983. Both entities collaborate with Devco in a [public–private partnership](/Public%E2%80%93private_partnership) focused on redeveloping the downtown core, with a particular emphasis on [transit-oriented development](/Transit-oriented_development). Boraie Development, a real estate firm based in New Brunswick, has also leveraged these incentives to undertake significant projects.

The [First Reformed Church](/First_Reformed_Church_of_New_Brunswick), erected in 1812, once stood as the tallest building in the city.
The National Bank of New Jersey, photographed in 1908.

#### Tallest Buildings

While no structures in New Brunswick surpass the 300-foot (91-meter) mark, the city's [skyline](/Skyline) has seen a notable increase in high-rise residential buildings since the turn of the millennium, many of which are clustered around the [New Brunswick station](/New_Brunswick_station), itself a product of 1960s construction. Of the 16 buildings exceeding 150 feet (46 meters), nine were erected in the 21st century, with several more approved or planned.

