### Geography

According to the [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), New Brunswick encompasses a total area of 5.75 square miles (14.90 km 2 ), of which 5.23 square miles (13.55 km 2 ) is land and 0.52 square miles (1.35 km 2 ) is water, representing 9.06% of the total area. The city is situated on the south side of the Raritan Valley, in proximity to municipalities such as [Piscataway](/Piscataway,_New_Jersey), [Highland Park](/Highland_Park,_New_Jersey), [Edison](/Edison,_New_Jersey), and [Franklin Township](/Franklin_Township,_Somerset_County,_New_Jersey). Geographically, it lies southwest of [Newark](/Newark,_New_Jersey) and New York City, and northeast of [Trenton](/Trenton,_New_Jersey) and Philadelphia.

New Brunswick shares borders with Piscataway, Highland Park, and Edison across the Raritan River, connected by the [Donald and Morris Goodkind Bridges](/Donald_and_Morris_Goodkind_Bridges). It also borders [North Brunswick](/North_Brunswick,_New_Jersey) to the southwest, [East Brunswick](/East_Brunswick,_New_Jersey) to the southeast, all within Middlesex County, and Franklin Township in [Somerset County](/Somerset_County,_New_Jersey).

While the city does not conduct elections based on a [ward](/Ward_(United_States)) system, it has historically been divided into such subdivisions. Several distinct [neighborhoods](/Local_government_in_New_Jersey) exist within the city, including the Fifth Ward, [Feaster Park](/Feaster_Park,_New_Brunswick), [Lincoln Park](/Lincoln_Park,_New_Brunswick,_New_Jersey), [Raritan Gardens](/Raritan_Gardens,_New_Jersey), and [Edgebrook](/Edgebrook,_New_Brunswick)-[Westons Mills](/Westons_Mills,_New_Jersey).

#### Climate

Under the [Köppen climate classification](/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification) system, New Brunswick experiences either a [hot-summer humid continental climate](/Hot-summer_humid_continental_climate) (Dfa) or a [humid subtropical climate](/Humid_subtropical_climate) (Cfa), depending on the specific isotherm used. The city is characterized by humid, hot summers and moderately cold winters, with precipitation distributed relatively evenly throughout the year, lacking a distinct wet or dry season. The average annual snowfall total, from October to April, is approximately 29 inches (74 cm), with February typically being the snowiest month, coinciding with the peak season for [nor'easters](/Nor%27easter).

