#### 2010 Census

The [2010 United States census](/2010_United_States_census) reported a population of 55,181 individuals residing in 14,119 households, with 7,751 families within the city. The [population density](/Population_density) was calculated at 10,556.4 people per square mile (4,075.8/km 2 ). There were 15,053 housing units, distributed at an average density of 2,879.7 per square mile (1,111.9/km 2 ). The racial composition was as follows: 45.43% (25,071) [White](/White_(U.S._census)), 16.04% (8,852) [Black or African American](/Black_(U.S._census)), 0.90% (498) [Native American](/Native_American_(U.S._census)), 7.60% (4,195) [Asian](/Asian_American), 0.03% (19) [Pacific Islander](/Pacific_Islander_(U.S._census)), 25.59% (14,122) identified with other races, and 4.39% (2,424) reported belonging to two or more races. Individuals identifying as [Hispanic or Latino](/Hispanic_(U.S._census)) of any race constituted 49.93% (27,553) of the total population.

Of the 14,119 households, 31.0% included children under the age of 18. Married couples comprised 29.2% of households, 17.5% were headed by a female with no husband present, and 45.1% were classified as non-family households. Approximately 25.8% of all households consisted of individuals living alone, and 7.2% were composed of individuals aged 65 or older. The average household size was 3.36, and the average family size was 3.91.

The age distribution showed 21.1% of the population under 18, 33.2% between 18 and 24, 28.4% between 25 and 44, 12.2% between 45 and 64, and 5.2% aged 65 or older. The median age was 23.3 years. For every 100 females, there were 105.0 males, and for every 100 females aged 18 and older, there were 105.3 males.

Data from the Census Bureau's 2006–2010 [American Community Survey](/American_Community_Survey), adjusted for [inflation](/Inflation_adjustment) to 2010 dollars, indicated a [median household income](/Median_household_income) of $44,543 (with a margin of error of ±$2,356) and a median family income of $44,455 (±$3,526). The median income for males was $31,313 (±$1,265), compared to $28,858 (±$1,771) for females. The [per capita income](/Per_capita_income) for the city was $16,395 (±$979). Approximately 15.5% of families and 25.8% of the population lived below the [poverty line](/Poverty_line), including 25.4% of those under 18 and 16.9% of those 65 or older.

#### 2000 Census

In the [2000 United States census](/2000_United_States_census), New Brunswick recorded a population of 48,573 residents, comprising 13,057 households and 7,207 families. The population density was 9,293.5 inhabitants per square mile (3,588.2/km 2 ). There were 13,893 housing units, with an average density of 2,658.1 per square mile (1,026.3/km 2 ). The racial makeup was reported as 51.7% [White](/White_(U.S._Census)), 24.5% [African American](/African_American_(U.S._Census)), 1.2% [Native American](/Native_American_(U.S._Census)), 5.9% [Asian](/Asian_American), 0.2% [Pacific Islander](/Pacific_Islander_(U.S._Census)), 21.0% from other races, and 4.2% from two or more races. Individuals identifying as [Hispanic](/Hispanic_(U.S._Census)) or [Latino](/Latino_(U.S._Census)) of any race accounted for 39.01% of the population.

Among the 13,057 households, 29.1% had children under 18 residing with them. Married couples constituted 29.6% of households, 18.0% were female-headed households without a husband present, and 44.8% were non-family households. Of all households, 24.3% were individual occupants, and 8.4% consisted of individuals aged 65 or older. The average household size was 3.23, and the average family size was 3.69.

The age distribution indicated that 20.1% of the population was under 18, 34.0% was between 18 and 24, 28.1% was between 25 and 44, 11.3% was between 45 and 64, and 6.5% was 65 or older. The median age was 24 years. For every 100 females, there were 98.4 males, and for every 100 females aged 18 and over, there were 96.8 males.

The [median household income](/Median_household_income) in the city was $36,080, with the median income for families being $38,222. Males reported a median income of $25,657, while females reported $23,604. The [per capita income](/Per_capita_income) for the city was $14,308. Notably, 27.0% of the population and 16.9% of families fell below the poverty line, with 25.9% of those under 18 and 13.8% of those 65 or older living in poverty.

### Economy

#### Healthcare Industry

The City Hall has actively promoted the nickname "The [Health Care](/Health_Care) City" to highlight the significant economic contribution of the healthcare sector. New Brunswick serves as the global headquarters for [Johnson & Johnson](/Johnson_%26_Johnson) and hosts several prominent medical teaching and research institutions. The [New Brunswick Health Sciences Technology High School](/New_Brunswick_Health_Sciences_Technology_High_School), a public high school operating under the [New Brunswick Public Schools](/New_Brunswick_Public_Schools) district, is described as the first secondary school program to directly affiliate with a [teaching hospital](/Teaching_hospital) and medical school, focusing its curriculum on [health sciences](/Health_sciences).

#### Urban Enterprise Zone

Certain areas within New Brunswick are designated as part of an [Urban Enterprise Zone](/Urban_Enterprise_Zone) (UEZ), a program encompassing 37 municipalities statewide. New Brunswick was selected in 2004 as one of two zones added to the program. This designation provides benefits aimed at stimulating employment and investment within the Zone, including a reduced [sales tax](/Sales_tax) rate of 3.3125% (half the statewide rate) for shoppers at eligible merchants. Established in December 2004, the city's Urban Enterprise Zone status is set to expire in December 2024.

### Arts and Culture

#### Theatre

The [New Brunswick Performing Arts Center](/New_Brunswick_Performing_Arts_Center), a contemporary cultural hub, opened its doors in 2019. It complements three existing professional venues: [Crossroads Theatre](/Crossroads_Theatre), designed by Parsons+Fernandez-Casteleiro Architects; [George Street Playhouse](/George_Street_Playhouse), established in 1974; and the historic [State Theatre](/State_Theatre,_New_Brunswick), originally built in 1921 for vaudeville and silent films. Notably, Crossroads Theatre received the prestigious [Tony Award](/Tony_Award) for Outstanding Regional Theatre in 1999, becoming the first [African American](/African_American) theater to achieve this honor. Crossroads Theatre also serves as the home for the [American Repertory Ballet](/American_Repertory_Ballet) and the Princeton Ballet School. Rutgers University contributes to the local theatre scene with student-run companies such as the Cabaret Theatre, The Livingston Theatre Company, and College Avenue Players, which stage a diverse range of productions, from musicals to dramatic plays and sketch comedy. In April 2025, the Rutgers Opera and Rutgers Symphony Orchestra of Rutgers University Mason Gross are scheduled to present a performance of *Carmen*.

A view looking north from the intersection of New and George Streets, with The Heldrich Center visible on the left.

#### Journalism

*New Brunswick Today*, a print and digital publication launched in 2011 by Rutgers journalism alumnus Charlie Kratovil, operates under the tagline "Independent news for the greater New Brunswick community." The publication has been recognized for its coverage of various civic issues, including those concerning the city's water utility, and was notably featured on [Full Frontal with Samantha Bee](/Full_Frontal_with_Samantha_Bee).

New Jersey's alternative weeklies, [The Aquarian Weekly](/The_Aquarian_Weekly) and NJ Indy, also provide coverage of the music and arts scene in New Brunswick.

#### Museums

New Brunswick is home to several significant cultural institutions, including the [Zimmerli Art Museum at Rutgers University](/Zimmerli_Art_Museum_at_Rutgers_University), founded in 1966; [Albus Cavus]; and the Rutgers University Geology Museum, established in 1872.

#### Fine Arts

During the 1950s through the 1970s, New Brunswick emerged as a vital center for avant-garde art, attracting artists such as [Allan Kaprow](/Allan_Kaprow), [George Segal](/George_Segal_(artist)), [George Brecht](/George_Brecht), [Robert Whitman](/Robert_Whitman), [Robert Watts](/Robert_Watts), [Lucas Samaras](/Lucas_Samaras), [Geoffrey Hendricks](/Geoffrey_Hendricks), [Wolf Vostell](/Wolf_Vostell), and [Roy Lichtenstein](/Roy_Lichtenstein). Many of these artists were affiliated with Rutgers University, and this collective was sometimes referred to as the "New Jersey School" or the "New Brunswick School of Painting." The YAM Festival, held on May 19, 1963, served as a platform for various artistic actions and [happenings](/Happening). Further exploration of this period can be found under [Fluxus at Rutgers University](/Fluxus_at_Rutgers_University).

#### Music

New Brunswick's live music scene has been a fertile ground for numerous original rock bands, with some achieving national recognition, including [The Smithereens](/The_Smithereens) and [Bon Jovi](/Bon_Jovi), alongside other notable local acts. The rock band [Looking Glass](/Looking_Glass_(band)), known for their 1972 Billboard Hot 100 number one hit "[Brandy (You're a Fine Girl)](/Brandy_(You%27re_a_Fine_Girl))," developed within the New Brunswick music scene and dedicated their debut album to the city's residents. Filmmaker [Paul Devlin](/Paul_Devlin_(filmmaker))'s inaugural documentary, *Rockin’ Brunswick* (1983), chronicled the city's vibrant rock scene of the 1980s.

The city is particularly recognized as a hub for local [punk rock](/Punk_rock) and underground music. [Alternative rock](/Alternative_rock), [indie rock](/Indie_rock), and [hardcore](/Hardcore_punk) music have long held sway in the city's live music venues. Many alternative rock bands gained significant radio airplay thanks to [Matt Pinfield](/Matt_Pinfield), who was an integral part of the New Brunswick music scene for over two decades, first at Rutgers University radio station [WRSU-FM](/WRSU-FM) and later at the alternative rock station [WHTG-FM](/WKMK).

Local pubs and clubs, such as the [Court Tavern](/Court_Tavern) and the [Melody Bar], provided stages for many local bands during the 1980s and 1990s. The city has been ranked fourth in New Jersey for its indie music scene.

The independent record label [Don Giovanni Records](/Don_Giovanni_Records) originated with the specific purpose of documenting the burgeoning New Brunswick basement music scene. In March 2017, [NJ.com](/NJ.com) remarked that "even if [Asbury Park](/Asbury_Park) has recently returned as our state's musical nerve center, with the brick-and-mortar venues and infrastructure to prove it, New Brunswick remains as the New Jersey scene's unadulterated, pounding heart." Several prominent local bands, including [Thursday](/Thursday_(band)) and [Ogbert the Nerd](/Ogbert_the_Nerd), formed within the city's dynamic live music landscape. The Rutgers radio station [WVPH 90.3 FM "The Core"](/WVPH) hosts the annual indie music festival "[Corefest](/Corefest)" on campus.

A variety of jazz organizations and festivals are active in the city, including the Hub City Jazz Festival and the New Brunswick Jazz Project. The New Brunswick Jazz Project is dedicated to promoting live jazz performances throughout the city and surrounding communities. New Brunswick also boasts a notable roster of rappers, including Trill Lik, Mello B, Amgjay, and GetBizzy Nino.

#### Film

New Brunswick hosts several [film festivals](/List_of_film_festivals_in_New_Jersey), two of which are presented by the [film society](/Film_society), the [Rutgers Film Co-op/New Jersey Media Arts Center]: the New Jersey Film Festival (established in 1982) and the United States Super 8mm Film + Digital Video Festival (around 1988). The Rutgers Jewish Film Festival was founded in 1999. The New Lens Film Festival is an annual event held at the [Mason Gross School of the Arts](/Mason_Gross_School_of_the_Arts).

#### Grease Trucks

The iconic "[Grease trucks](/Grease_trucks)," a collection of [truck-based food vendors](/Food_truck) situated on the [College Avenue Campus](/College_Avenue_Campus) at Rutgers, were renowned for their signature "[Fat Sandwiches](/Fat_Sandwich)" – sub rolls packed with fried ingredients. In 2013, the grease trucks were relocated to various other areas of the Rutgers-New Brunswick Campus to facilitate the construction of a new Rutgers building.

### Government

The administrative heart of New Brunswick is located in its [Civic Square](/Civic_Square,_New_Brunswick) district, which houses City Hall, the [New Brunswick Free Public Library](/New_Brunswick_Free_Public_Library), and the [New Brunswick Main Post Office](/New_Brunswick_Main_Post_Office), alongside numerous other municipal, county, state, and federal offices.

#### Local Government

**City Hall**

The governance of the City of New Brunswick operates under the [Faulkner Act](/Faulkner_Act), officially titled the Optional Municipal Charter Law, employing a [Mayor-Council](/Faulkner_Act_(mayor%E2%80%93council)) system. New Brunswick is one of 71 municipalities across New Jersey (out of 564) that utilize this form of government. The city's governing body consists of the Mayor and a five-member City Council, all elected [at-large](/At-large) on a partisan basis for four-year terms. These elections coincide with the November general election in even-numbered years. The City Council members are elected in a staggered manner, with either two or three seats up for election every two years. The mayoral election occurs concurrently with the election for two council seats. The City Council functions as the legislative branch of New Brunswick's municipal government, responsible for approving the annual budget, ordinances, resolutions, contracts, and appointments to various boards and commissions. The Council President, elected by the council members to a two-year term during a reorganization meeting following the election, presides over all council meetings.

As of 2024, [Democrat](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) James Cahill holds the office of the 62nd [mayor of New Brunswick](/List_of_mayors_of_New_Brunswick,_New_Jersey). He assumed the mayoral duties on January 1, 1991, and his current term extends until December 31, 2026. The current members of the City Council include Council President Rebecca H. Escobar (D, 2026), Council Vice President John A. Anderson (D, 2024), Manuel J. Castañeda (D, 2024), Matthew Ferguson (D, 2026; appointed to fill an unexpired term), Glenn J. Fleming (D, 2024), Petra N. Gaskins (D, 2026), and Suzanne M. Sicora Ludwig (D, 2024).

In January 2024, the city council appointed Matthew Ferguson to fill the vacant council seat with a term ending in December 2026. This position was previously held by [Kevin Egan](/Kevin_Egan_(New_Jersey_politician)), who resigned earlier that month to assume a seat in the [New Jersey General Assembly](/New_Jersey_General_Assembly). Ferguson will serve in an interim capacity until the November general election, when voters will select a candidate to complete the remaining term.

The City Council was expanded from five to seven members in January 2023. Petra N. Gaskins was sworn in as the first Black woman and the youngest individual in the city's history to hold such a position, while Manuel J. Castañeda became the first Latino man elected to the City Council.

#### Emergency Services

##### Police Department

The New Brunswick Police Department has been the subject of considerable public attention due to various incidents throughout its history. In 1991, the fatal shooting of Shaun Potts, an unarmed Black resident, by Sergeant Zane Grey prompted widespread local protests. In 1996, Officer James Consalvo fatally shot Carolyn "Sissy" Adams, an unarmed prostitute who had reportedly bitten him. The Adams case ignited calls for reform within the New Brunswick Police Department, culminating in a settlement with her family. In 2001, two officers, Sgt. Marco Chinchilla and Det. James Marshall, were convicted for their involvement in running a bordello; Chinchilla received a three-year sentence, and Marshall received four years. In 2011, Officer Brad Berdel fatally shot [Barry Deloatch](/Barry_Deloatch), a Black man who had fled from police, though authorities claimed he had attacked officers with a stick. This incident triggered daily protests from residents.

Following the Deloatch shooting, Sergeant Richard Rowe faced formal charges for mishandling 81 Internal Affairs investigations. Mayor Cahill emphasized that these actions were intended to "rebuild the public's trust and confidence in local law enforcement."

##### Fire Department

The current professional city fire department was established in 1914, although the city's first volunteer fire company dates back to 1764. The department operates from three stations and comprises approximately 90 officers and firefighters.

In 2014, the city faced public criticism after its fire director, Robert Rawls, whose driving record was marked by numerous accidents and license suspensions, struck three children in a crosswalk while operating a city-owned vehicle.

#### Federal, State, and County Representation

New Brunswick is situated within the 6th Congressional District and is part of New Jersey's 17th state legislative district.

For the [119th United States Congress](/119th_United_States_Congress), [New Jersey's 6th congressional district](/New_Jersey%27s_6th_congressional_district) is represented by [Frank Pallone](/Frank_Pallone) (D), who resides in [Long Branch](/Long_Branch,_New_Jersey). New Jersey's representation in the [United States Senate](/United_States_Senate) is held by [Democrats](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) Cory Booker (from [Newark](/Newark,_New_Jersey), term ending 2027) and [Andy Kim](/Andy_Kim) (from [Moorestown](/Moorestown,_New_Jersey), term ending 2031).

In the [2024-2025 session](/221st_New_Jersey_Legislature), the [17th legislative district](/New_Jersey%27s_17th_legislative_district) of the [New Jersey Legislature](/New_Jersey_Legislature) is represented in the [State Senate](/New_Jersey_Senate) by Bob Smith (D) of [Piscataway](/Piscataway,_New_Jersey), and in the [General Assembly](/New_Jersey_General_Assembly) by Joseph Danielsen (D) of [Franklin Township](/Franklin_Township,_Somerset_County,_New_Jersey) and Kevin Egan (D) of New Brunswick.

The [Middlesex County](/Middlesex_County,_New_Jersey) government is overseen by a [Board of County Commissioners](/Board_of_County_Commissioners_(New_Jersey)). Its seven members are elected [at-large](/At-large) on a partisan basis for three-year terms, with elections staggered annually. The board convenes an annual reorganization meeting in January to elect a commissioner director and deputy director. As of 2025, the Middlesex County Commissioners include Director Ronald G. Rios (D, [Carteret](/Carteret,_New_Jersey), 2027); Deputy Director Shanti Narra (D, [North Brunswick](/North_Brunswick,_New_Jersey), 2027); Claribel A. "Clary" Azcona-Barber (D, New Brunswick, 2025); Charles Kenny (D, [Woodbridge Township](/Woodbridge_Township,_New_Jersey), 2025); Leslie Koppel (D, [Monroe Township](/Monroe_Township,_Middlesex_County,_New_Jersey), 2026); Chanelle Scott McCullum (D, [Piscataway](/Piscataway,_New_Jersey), 2025); and Charles E. Tomaro (D, [Edison](/Edison,_New_Jersey), 2026).

The county's constitutional officers for 2025 are Clerk Nancy Pinkin (D, [East Brunswick](/East_Brunswick,_New_Jersey)); Sheriff Mildred S. Scott (D, Piscataway); and Surrogate Claribel Cortes (D, North Brunswick, 2026).

#### Politics

As of March 23, 2011, New Brunswick had 22,742 registered voters. Of these, 38.4% (8,732) were registered as [Democrats](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)), 3.9% (882) as [Republicans](/Republican_Party_(United_States)), and 57.6% (13,103) as [Unaffiliated](/Unaffiliated_(New_Jersey)). An additional 25 voters were registered with other parties.

