### Education

#### Public Schools

The [New Brunswick Public Schools](/New_Brunswick_Public_Schools) district serves students from pre-kindergarten through twelfth grade. As one of the 31 former [Abbott districts](/Abbott_district) in New Jersey, it operates under special funding mandates established by the [New Jersey Supreme Court](/New_Jersey_Supreme_Court) decision in *Abbott v. Burke*. These districts are now referred to as "SDA Districts," with the state bearing the full cost of school construction and renovation projects under the guidance of the [New Jersey Schools Development Authority](/New_Jersey_Schools_Development_Authority). The district's Board of Education, comprising nine members elected at-large, has three seats up for election annually in April for three-year terms. Prior to 2012, the Board members were appointed by the city's mayor.

During the 2022–23 academic year, the district encompassed 12 schools and enrolled 9,690 students, supported by 777.4 full-time equivalent (FTE) classroom teachers, resulting in a [student–teacher ratio](/Student%E2%80%93teacher_ratio) of 12.5:1. The schools within the district include:

*   Lincoln Elementary School [293] (578 students; grades K-4)
*   Livingston Elementary School [294] (342 students; grades K-5)
*   Lord Stirling Elementary School [295] (490 students; grades PreK-5)
*   McKinley Community Elementary School [296] (640 students; grades PreK-8)
*   A. Chester Redshaw Elementary School [297] (784 students; grades PreK-5)
*   Paul Robeson Community School For The Arts [298] (665 students; grades K-8)
*   Roosevelt Elementary School [299] (609 students; grades K-5)
*   Blanquita B. Valenti Community School [300] (opened 2023-24: 569 students; grades 4–8)
*   Woodrow Wilson Elementary School [301] (373 students; grades PreK-8)
*   New Brunswick Middle School [302] (1,259 students; grades 6–8)
*   [New Brunswick High School](/New_Brunswick_High_School) [303] (2,477 students; grades 9–12)

The [Greater Brunswick Charter School](/Greater_Brunswick_Charter_School), a K–8 charter school serving students from New Brunswick, [Edison](/Edison,_New_Jersey), [Highland Park](/Highland_Park,_New_Jersey), and [Milltown](/Milltown,_New_Jersey), also provides educational services to the community. For the 2021–22 school year, it reported an enrollment of 399 students and 32.5 FTE classroom teachers, yielding a [student–teacher ratio](/Student%E2%80%93teacher_ratio) of 12.3:1.

Eighth-grade students from across Middlesex County are eligible to apply for the specialized high school programs offered by the [Middlesex County Magnet Schools](/Middlesex_County_Magnet_Schools). This county-wide vocational school district provides full-time career and technical education at its campuses in [East Brunswick](/East_Brunswick_Magnet_School), [Edison](/Edison_Academy_Magnet_School), [Perth Amboy](/Perth_Amboy_Magnet_School), [Piscataway](/Piscataway_Magnet_School), and [Woodbridge](/Woodbridge_Academy_Magnet_School), with no tuition fees for enrolled students.

#### Higher Education

*   [Rutgers University](/Rutgers_University%E2%80%93New_Brunswick) operates three campuses within the city: the College Avenue Campus (serving as the university's administrative center), Douglass Campus, and Cook Campus, with some areas extending into adjacent townships. The university also maintains two other campuses in [Piscataway](/Piscataway,_New_Jersey), located across the [Raritan River](/Raritan_River) from New Brunswick. In recent decades, Rutgers has expanded its presence downtown, adding both academic and residential facilities.
*   New Brunswick is home to the [New Brunswick Theological Seminary](/New_Brunswick_Theological_Seminary), an institution of the [Reformed Church in America](/Reformed_Church_in_America), established in New York in 1784 and relocated to New Brunswick in 1810.
*   The [Robert Wood Johnson Medical School](/Robert_Wood_Johnson_Medical_School), affiliated with [Rutgers University](/Rutgers_University), has campuses in both New Brunswick and Piscataway.
*   [Middlesex County College](/Middlesex_County_College) operates some facilities in the downtown area, although its main campus is located in Edison.

#### Historic District

The [Livingston Avenue Historic District], situated along Livingston Avenue between Hale and Morris Streets, was added to the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on February 16, 1996. Its designation recognizes its historical significance in architecture, social history, and urban development between 1870 and 1929.

*   The John B. Drury House, an example of Victorian architecture.
*   Roosevelt Intermediate School, showcasing Neo-Classical Revival style.
*   Ukrainian Catholic Church, built in the Richardsonian Romanesque style.

### Infrastructure

#### Transportation

##### Roads and Highways

As of May 2010, New Brunswick's road network spanned 73.24 miles (117.87 km). Of this total, 56.13 miles (90.33 km) are maintained by the municipality, 8.57 miles (13.79 km) by Middlesex County, 7.85 miles (12.63 km) by the [New Jersey Department of Transportation](/New_Jersey_Department_of_Transportation), and 0.69 miles (1.11 km) by the [New Jersey Turnpike Authority](/New_Jersey_Turnpike_Authority).

The city is traversed by a network of roads and highways, including the intersection of [US 1](/U.S._Route_1_in_New_Jersey) and [Route 18](/New_Jersey_Route_18), and is bisected by [Route 27](/New_Jersey_Route_27). A short segment of the [New Jersey Turnpike](/New_Jersey_Turnpike) ([I-95](/Interstate_95_in_New_Jersey)) runs through the city, with ramps providing access to Exit 9, located just outside the city limits in [East Brunswick](/East_Brunswick,_New_Jersey). Nearby major roadways include the [Garden State Parkway](/Garden_State_Parkway) in [Woodbridge](/Woodbridge_Township,_New_Jersey) and [I-287](/Interstate_287) in neighboring Edison, Piscataway, and Franklin townships.

The New Brunswick Parking Authority manages 14 parking facilities throughout the city, comprising both ground-level and multi-story structures. CitiPark operates a downtown parking facility located at 2 Albany Street.

##### Public Transportation

New Brunswick is a key transit hub, served by both [NJ Transit](/NJ_Transit) and [Amtrak](/Amtrak) trains on the [Northeast Corridor Line](/Northeast_Corridor_Line). NJ Transit offers frequent service northbound to [New York Penn Station](/New_York_Penn_Station) and southbound to [Trenton](/Trenton_Transit_Center). Amtrak's [Keystone Service](/Keystone_Service) and [Northeast Regional](/Northeast_Regional) trains also make stops at the [New Brunswick Station](/New_Brunswick_station). The [Jersey Avenue Station](/Jersey_Avenue_station) is another station served by Northeast Corridor trains. For additional Amtrak connections, passengers can utilize NJ Transit services to reach New York Penn Station, [Newark](/Newark_Penn_Station), Trenton, or [Metropark](/Metropark_station).

Local bus services are provided by NJ Transit routes 810, 811, 814, 815, and 818. The extensive [Rutgers Campus bus network](/Rutgers_Campus_Buses) is also available. Middlesex County Area Transit (MCAT) operates shuttles connecting various points across the county, including the M1 route, which runs between [Jamesburg](/Jamesburg,_New_Jersey) and the [New Brunswick Train Station](/New_Brunswick_station). DASH/CAT buses, managed by [Somerset County](/Somerset_County,_New_Jersey) on routes 851 and 852, provide service between New Brunswick and [Bound Brook](/Bound_Brook,_New_Jersey).

[Suburban Trails] offers intercity bus service connecting New Brunswick to [New York City](/New_York_City) via routes operating on 42nd Street and along Wall Street in [Lower Manhattan](/Lower_Manhattan). Studies are currently underway to establish the [New Brunswick Bus Rapid Transit](/New_Brunswick_Bus_Rapid_Transit) system. Intercity bus services from New Brunswick to [Columbia, Maryland](/Columbia,_Maryland), and [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.) are provided by OurBus Prime.

Historically, New Brunswick served as the eastern terminus of the [Delaware & Raritan Canal](/Delaware_and_Raritan_Canal), with remnants of the canal still visible or restored along the river. Until 1936, the city was also serviced by the interurban [Newark–Trenton Fast Line](/Newark%E2%80%93Trenton_Fast_Line), a 72-mile (116 km) route connecting [Jersey City](/Jersey_City,_New_Jersey) and [Trenton](/Trenton,_New_Jersey), with a stop in New Brunswick.

The [Raritan River Railroad](/Raritan_River_Railroad) once served New Brunswick, though this segment of the line is now defunct. The track and [freight station](/Raritan_River_Freight_Station) remain. Proposals have been put forth to repurpose this line as a [light rail](/Light_rail) route, offering an alternative to commuters currently driving on Route 18.

The closest airport providing air transportation services is [Old Bridge Airport](/Old_Bridge_Airport) in [Old Bridge](/Old_Bridge_Township,_New_Jersey), offering short-distance flights. The nearest commercial airports are [Princeton Airport](/Princeton_Airport_(New_Jersey)), located 14 miles (23 km) southwest, and [Newark Liberty International Airport](/Newark_Liberty_International_Airport), a major hub for [United Airlines](/United_Airlines), situated 22 miles (35 km) north of New Brunswick.

#### Healthcare

[Robert Wood Johnson University Hospital](/Robert_Wood_Johnson_University_Hospital)'s main campus is located in New Brunswick.

[Saint Peter's University Hospital](/Saint_Peter%27s_University_Hospital), [Robert Wood Johnson University Hospital](/Robert_Wood_Johnson_University_Hospital), [Robert Wood Johnson Medical School](/Robert_Wood_Johnson_Medical_School), the [Cancer Institute of New Jersey](/Cancer_Institute_of_New_Jersey), and [The Bristol-Myers Squibb Children's Hospital](/The_Bristol-Myers_Squibb_Children%27s_Hospital) are all situated within New Brunswick. The city's designation as the "Healthcare City" is well-earned due to its extensive network of public and private healthcare services.

### Popular Culture

*   On April 18, 1872, in New Brunswick, [William Cameron Coup](/William_Cameron_Coup) pioneered a system for transporting circus equipment, personnel, and animals between cities via railroad cars. This innovative system was subsequently adopted by other railroad circuses and remained in use throughout the golden age of such enterprises until the closure of the [Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus](/Ringling_Bros._and_Barnum_%26_Bailey_Circus) in 2017.
*   The 1980s sitcom, [Charles in Charge](/Charles_in_Charge), was set in New Brunswick.
*   The 2004 film [Harold and Kumar Go To White Castle](/Harold_and_Kumar_Go_To_White_Castle) centers on Harold and Kumar's quest to reach a [White Castle](/White_Castle_(restaurant)) and includes a scene set in a fictionalized version of New Brunswick.
*   The 2007 [Pulitzer Prize](/Pulitzer_Prize)-winning novel [The Brief Wondrous Life of Oscar Wao](/The_Brief_Wondrous_Life_of_Oscar_Wao) is primarily set in New Brunswick.
*   In [Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie](/Chimamanda_Ngozi_Adichie)'s 2013 novel [Americanah](/Americanah), a taxi driver boasts about his daughter being on the dean's list at Rutgers.
*   The independent record label [Don Giovanni Records](/Don_Giovanni_Records) was founded in 2003 to document the music scene in New Brunswick.

### Points of Interest

The Heldrich in Downtown New Brunswick, a landmark of the city's revitalization.

*   The [Albany Street Bridge](/Albany_Street_Bridge), a seven-span stone arch bridge dating to 1892, once served as a segment of the transcontinental [Lincoln Highway](/Lincoln_Highway). Spanning 595 feet (181 m) across the Raritan River, it connects New Brunswick to [Highland Park](/Highland_Park,_New_Jersey).
*   [Bishop House](/Bishop_House_(New_Brunswick,_New_Jersey)), located at 115 College Avenue, is an [Italianate architecture](/Italianate_architecture) mansion constructed for James Bishop. It was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1976.
*   The historic [Old Queens Campus](/Old_Queens) and [Voorhees Mall](/Voorhees_Mall) at [Rutgers University](/Rutgers_University%E2%80%93New_Brunswick). Old Queens, built in 1809, is the oldest building on the Rutgers campus, with its cornerstone laid in 1809.
*   [Buccleuch Mansion] in Buccleuch Park. Originally built in 1739 by Anthony White as part of a working farm and residence overlooking Raritan Landing, the house and its adjacent 79 acres (32 ha) were deeded to the City of New Brunswick in 1911 to be preserved as a park.
*   [Christ Church Episcopal Churchyard](/Christ_Church_Episcopal_Churchyard,_New_Brunswick) features its earliest burial from 1754 and includes the gravesites of enslaved individuals.
*   The [Henry Guest House], added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1976, is a Georgian stone farmhouse built in 1760 by Henry Guest. It was relocated in 1924 adjacent to the New Brunswick Free Public Library after plans for its demolition at the original site were made.
*   [William H. Johnson House] exemplifies [Italianate architecture](/Italianate_architecture), built around 1870 during a post-Civil War economic boom in New Brunswick. Its architectural features, including tall narrow windows with arched tops, double bays, cornice brackets, and low-pitched roofs, are characteristic of the Italianate style. The house was added to the National Register of Historic Places in July 2006.
*   St. Peter the Apostle Church, constructed in 1856 and designed by Patrick Keeley, is situated at 94 Somerset Street.
*   The [Delaware and Raritan Canal](/Delaware_and_Raritan_Canal), completed in 1834, reached its zenith in the 1860s and 1870s, primarily serving to transport coal from Pennsylvania to New York City. Accessing the canal at [Bordentown](/Bordentown,_New_Jersey) on the [Delaware River](/Delaware_River), the main route extended 44 miles (71 km) to New Brunswick on the Raritan River.
*   The birthplace of poet [Joyce Kilmer](/Joyce_Kilmer), located on Joyce Kilmer Avenue, is the site where the poet and essayist was born on December 6, 1886. The building, acquired by a local [American Legion](/American_Legion) post, and its second-floor memorial to Kilmer, were sold to the state in the 1960s and subsequently transferred to the ownership of the City of New Brunswick.
*   The site of [Johnson & Johnson](/Johnson_%26_Johnson) world headquarters.
*   The [Willow Grove Cemetery](/Willow_Grove_Cemetery,_New_Brunswick), located behind the [Henry Guest House] and the [New Brunswick Free Public Library], was acquired in the late 1840s. The cemetery association was incorporated in 1850, and a state charter was granted the following year.
*   The grave of [Mary Ellis](/Mary_Ellis_grave) (1750–1828) is notable for its location within the AMC Theatres parking lot on [U.S. Route 1](/U.S._Route_1_in_New_Jersey), downstream from downtown New Brunswick.
*   [Lawrence Brook](/Lawrence_Brook), a tributary of the [Raritan River](/Raritan_River), has a watershed covering 48 square miles (120 km 2 ) that includes New Brunswick, as well as [East Brunswick](/East_Brunswick,_New_Jersey), [Milltown](/Milltown,_New_Jersey), [North Brunswick](/North_Brunswick,_New_Jersey), and [South Brunswick](/South_Brunswick,_New_Jersey).
*   [Elmer B. Boyd Park], a 20-acre (8.1 ha) park running along the Raritan River adjacent to Route 18, underwent an $11 million renovation and reopened to the public in 1999.

